{
  "decision_summary": "The chip temperature (89.16°C) exceeds the limit (85.0°C). Previous attempts to increase spreader width hit geometry bounds. The strategy shifts to increasing the heat spreader's thermal conductivity, which is currently at a moderate level (500.0 W/mK is not the bound, wait—checking editable vars: bounds are [20.0, 500.0]. Ah, the current state shows 500.0. I cannot increase conductivity further as it is already at the upper bound of 500.0. \n\nRe-evaluating options:\n- materials.spreader_material.conductivity: Current 500.0, Max 500.0. Cannot increase.\n- components.2.width: Current 0.84, Max 1.0. Can increase. Previous invalid proposal was 1.008 (slightly over). A value of 0.95 or 1.0 is valid.\n- components.2.height: Current 0.15, Max 0.18. Can increase.\n- components.2.x0: Current 0.25. Chip center is 0.45 + 0.15 = 0.60. Moving spreader right towards chip center is viable.\n\nThe history note says 'geometry changes are hitting legality limits', but the specific invalid proposal was 1.008 for width. The bound is 1.0. So setting width to exactly 1.0 is a valid, high-impact move that hasn't been successfully tried yet. Also, height can be increased from 0.15 to 0.18.\n\nLet's try increasing the spreader width to the maximum allowed (1.0) and slightly increasing height to maximize cross-sectional area for heat spreading, as material conductivity is maxed out.",
  "changes": [
    {
      "path": "components.2.width",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 0.84,
      "new": 1.0,
      "reason": "Maximize lateral heat spreading area by extending the spreader to the allowable domain width limit. Previous attempt failed due to slight overshoot; this sets it exactly to the bound."
    },
    {
      "path": "components.2.height",
      "action": "set",
      "old": 0.15,
      "new": 0.18,
      "reason": "Increase vertical thermal cross-section to reduce resistance between chip and spreader, complementing the width increase."
    }
  ],
  "expected_effects": [
    "Reduce chip peak temperature below 85.0°C by improving geometric heat spreading capacity.",
    "Lower overall thermal resistance of the heat spreader component."
  ],
  "risk_notes": [
    "Geometry changes may approach domain boundaries; ensure no overlap violations occur with other components (chip is at y=0.2, spreader y=0.32, so vertical expansion up to 0.18 puts top at 0.50, which is the domain edge, safe).",
    "If these geometric maxima are insufficient, the design may be fundamentally constrained by the fixed boundary conditions or maxed-out material properties."
  ]
}
